Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["The rules derived from geodesic equations", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.926488660902029*^9, 3.926488692214422*^9}, {
  3.926491103913084*^9, 
  3.926491107883545*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"dec90f6a-ea6e-ed4d-afd0-\
3602b24e74c2"],

Cell["\<\
The conditions on the metric, all them are derived from the geodesic equation \
of the inertial observer\[CloseCurlyQuote]s worldline and from the \
consequence that the tetrads are parallely transported along this curve.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{3.9264911104582844`*^9, 
  3.9265629777501755`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"b046d4a1-161f-fb4a-ac05-\
f77bb704f24f"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Conditions and rules on the metric ", "Subsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.92656407620072*^9, 
  3.926564095345356*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"96844a5e-b30f-3945-a9ef-\
e96b37179478"],

Cell["\<\
These are the rules we define as rule as of now, and as mentioned above. \
These rules put the derivative of the metric to vanish on the worldline. And \
there are alternate rules we can define to achieve this and has to defines \
for specific indices and respect the symmetries of the tensor (here the \
metric tensor). We can use the MakeRule from xAct or the ordinary rule from \
Wolfram Language to do this as shown below.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9265641077024536`*^9, 3.926564222885578*^9}, {
  3.926564276408497*^9, 
  3.926564375831951*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"1ff39481-60e0-2043-8a64-\
1258dc0d2e72"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{"metricrule3", " ", "=", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"PDPDmetric", "[", 
    RowBox[{"_", ",", "_", ",", "_", ",", 
     RowBox[{"_", "?", "TangentM1`Q"}]}], "]"}], "->", 
   "0"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{"metricrule31", " ", "=", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"PDPDmetric", "[", 
    RowBox[{"_", ",", "_", ",", 
     RowBox[{"_", "?", "TangentM1`Q"}], ",", "_"}], "]"}], "->", 
   "0"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{"metricrulea", "=", 
  RowBox[{"MakeRule", "[", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"{", 
